{
  "texts": [
    "Visualization tools-like token-level reward heatmaps, per-layer rank evolution dashboards, and attention flow diagrams-will help interpret the learning process more transparently.",
    "DRaFT-Q provides a strong foundation for scalable, interpretable fine-tuning-and with these future enhancements, it may serve as a general framework for adaptive neural optimization.",
    "ConclusionIn this work, we presented extbfDRaFT-Q (Dynamic Rank-Aware Fine-Tuning under Quantization), a novel and lightweight PEFT method that enables effective fine-tuning of large language models (LLMs) under quantized, memoryconstrained settings.",
    "DRaFT-Q introduces two innovations: extbfdynamic rank allocation, which allows LoRA adapters to grow or shrink based on real-time training signals, and extbfreward-weighted loss, which directs optimization towards semantically relevant tokens.",
    "Together, these mechanisms ensure efficient parameter utilization while enhancing learning stability and convergence.Comprehensive experiments across reasoning and dialogue tasks-CommonsenseQA, OpenBookQA, GSM8K, OpenAssistant, OpenHermes, and UltraChat-demonstrate the efficacy of DRaFT-Q."
  ]
}